{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4425f3c4-a641-4d04-add8-976fe7977bac","content":"**Use `dotnet-trace`** — it's the easiest option for .NET apps and doesn't require installing full profiling suites.\n\n### Quick steps:\n\n```powershell\n# 1. Install the tool (one-time)\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\n\n# 2. Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# 3. Collect a CPU profile (runs ~30s, adjust as needed)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis produces a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Alternatives worth knowing:\n| Tool | When to use |\n|---|---|\n| **PerfView** | Deeper OS-level + .NET analysis (ETW-based) |\n| **dotnet-counters** | Quick real-time check before tracing (`dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>`) |\n| **Windows Performance Recorder (WPR)** | Full system-wide kernel + user traces |\n\n**Tip:** Run `dotnet-counters monitor -p <PID>` first to confirm CPU is actually in your managed code (vs. native/GC), then collect the trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c6173adf-2b0c-4f9a-af6a-d54ec655fc6e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":346},"id":"8659f6bc-7893-45f2-ae8d-ebf9e8d911c6","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:46:56.268Z","parentId":"0681c131-d2b6-436f-b6e8-5e8dcf377640"}
